photos.Observation Details: At least 6 along Red Road between 5:30 and 6:00.  Saw 6 birds on road (or their eye shine).  Heard 2 birds singing as it was getting light that I believe were additional birds.  I did not play a tape, but a couple of birds flew in towards me.  Perhaps attracted by my light?  It was interesting seeing a pair of glowing eyes flying towards me.  They did not appear concerned with my presence, my light, or the flash from my camera.  They would fly-catch right in front of me sometimes landing about 10 feet away.

Circled overhead in good light for about 2 minutes.  Had good looks.  Could see that they were large swifts that were black below with the primaries and secondaries appearing to be lighter in color, a grayish black.  Sometimes would spread their tails which also at times appeared slightly notched.  Very poor photos show that the shape is that of a swift and that the shape is not that of a Vaux’s Swift nor a Purple Martin.  The photos also show that there is no white underneath ruling out White-throated Swifts.

photos.Observation Details: Confirmed by hummingbird bander - Susan Campbell, Southern Pines, NC Also, in "Hummingbirds of North America", it says, " 30% of adult female Allens's show distinct to extensive rufous edgings on their uppertail coverts, versus narrow to absent edgings on adult femal Rufous.  Thus, extensive rufous on the uppertail-coverts is strongly indicative of Allen's."  This trait appears to be visible in these pictures.

Found by John Toldi.  Plump, gray shorebirds same size as accompanying Black Turnstones.  Turnstones black, Surfbirds gray.  Surfbirds definitely lighter in comparison to Turnstones.  Yellow legs obvious.  Mostly roosting, but when spread wings and/or flew, solid gray back contrasted with a white upper tail / rump followed by a strong black band on tip of tail.  White stripes on wings.  Two clumps/flocks near the end of the rock jetty that comes down from Brooks Island. Distant scope views from Ferry Point.  Tide moderately high.

Continuing birds originally reported by Albert Linkowski.  Located on the near end of the pond closest to the train tracks, but the birds were still seen from a distance.  Scope looks were not the best, but better than the photos taken.  Mixed in with Red-necked Phalaropes.  The Wilson’s were slightly larger and had longer, thinner bills than the Red-necked.  The faces of the Wilson’s appeared to be of more uniformed coloration due to the lack of a black eye patch.  The backs of the Wilson’s appeared to be of a lighter, more uniformed gray coloration than the Red-necked.

Breeding plumage adult sitting on the water near Brook’s Island.  Relative size of bird and bill looked too small for a Laughing Gull.  When it spread it’s wings, could tell it was not a Bonaparte’s.  Bird then got up and with great luck flew directly over my head. Got good looks at the wing tips with strong white patterning on the tips and also white separating the black on the tips from the rest of the wing. Unfortunately, I did not get a picture of the flying bird.  After flying over my head, it appeared to fly off in the direction of Miller Knox.  Update: Ethan Monk notified me that the same bird was likely seen a couple hours later at Fort Baker in Marin County by Derek Lecy  https://ebird.org/checklist/S71401152
